Serbia regarded Kosovo as the birthplace and cultural cradle of the nation, because Serbia had established its strongest country in the 12th century, and the Albanians moved in large numbers only after the invasion of the Ottoman Empire and the defeat of the Serbian army to the north.
The Albanians, for their part, insisted that the primitive tribes that lived in Kosovo in the 4th and 5th centuries BC were the ancestors of the Albanians, and therefore Kosovo has been an Albanian territory since ancient times.
The subjective political division has led to fierce clashes between different ethnicities, religions and cultures, creating fierce confrontations between Serbs and Albanians in the Kosovo region.
