Italy's Eurosceptic government aims to be the equivalent of 2.4% of gross domestic product (GDP) in the next three years, suggesting that there is still no debt reduction in the face of deficit reduction requirements.
The European Commission on Economic Affairs Executive (EC) Economic Affairs Commission, Moscovici, said on Friday that “we have no interest in the crisis between the Commission and Italy ” and that he responded cautiously because the EU ’ s proposals and sanctions could have little impact on Italy.
EU officials and diplomats still hope that market forces will persuade Italy to adjust its budget plan ahead of Italy's formal submission to the EU's executive board in mid-October.
After the government announced its plans, the euro fell to its lowest level in nearly two weeks on Friday, and the yield on Italian bonds touched its highest level in three weeks.
If the deficit target remains unchanged by the October deadline, the European Commission would likely veto Italy's draft budget, something the Commission has never done to any country.
EU Executive Vice President Tony Bovsky said at a meeting in Latvia's capital Riga on Friday that Italy's current fiscal plan "appears to be inconsistent with the Stability and Growth Pact," referring to the bloc's fiscal regulations.
