According to the trade agreement subsidiary arrangements announced Monday, the new U.S.-Mexico-Canada trade agreement will retain U.S. President Donald Trump's ability to implement the threat of a 25% tariff on imported cars, while at the same time making passenger cars, pickups and car parts imported from Canada and Mexico essentially exempt from paying tariffs.
If Trump imposes so-called "232 Chapter" tariffs on cars for national security reasons, then Mexico and Canada will have a passenger car quota that is exempt from paying taxes for $2.20 million vehicles exported to the United States every year.
Under the subsidiary arrangements, pickup trucks produced in both countries will be fully exempted from the tariff.
If Trump imposes auto tariffs, Mexico will receive a tax quota of $1,0.8 billion a billion dollars a year, and Canada will receive a $324 billion quota.
Both quotas are much higher than the existing output levels in both countries, providing room for growth for exports between the two countries.
WASHINGTON / MEXICO CHAN (Reuters) - After days of controversy, U.S. President Donald Trump's government and Canada are making concrete efforts to resolve trade policy differences, raising hopes that the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) is expected to maintain the form of the trilateral agreement.
Despite the lack of details, the above-mentioned apparent progress is enough to prompt the Mexican and U.S. governments to abruptly halt plans to publish the text of the two-party trade agreement, giving Canada more time to join the agreement.
