“In the next 48 hours, we ’ ll know if we ’ re going to have a text of a tripartite agreement or have to publish the texts of the two-party agreement, ” Guajardo said.
Guajardo said his U.S. and Canadian counterparts "specially requested" to delay the release of the text.
A spokesman for the U.S. Trade Representative ’ s Office (USTR) did not comment on the text of the U.S.-Mexico-Canada trade agreement and the U.S.-Canada consultations.
Officials from the Office of the Prime Minister of Canada and the Office of the Foreign Minister did not respond to requests for comment on the counter-recommencement.
According to foreign media reports, in a conservation center on the outskirts of Pretoria, the capital of South Africa, two lions play together, and it is difficult to see any anomalies, but they are unique.
The University of Pretoria declared: “This is the first young lion born in artificial insemination – the first in the world. ”
Intensive scientists are working on the reproductive system of the Mother African Lion.
Ganswint, director of the Mammal Research Institute at the University of Pretoria, said that the two young lions, born on August 25th, are quite healthy and normal.
After eighteen months of intensive trials, his team finally made the breakthrough.
Ganswint said in an interview with the media: "We collected sperm from a healthy lion."
Next, the researchers, etc., when the hormone content in the mother's body reaches the right level, artificially insemination for it.
Ganswint said, "Fortunately, the result was a success."
He said the researchers "done attempts several times, but unexpectedly, didn't cost much effort."
He said that the above-mentioned research breakthrough can be repeated, and scientists hope to use this technology to save large cats on the verge of extinction.
The International Union for Conservation of Nature notes that lions have been extinct in 26 African countries, with the total number of surviving wild lions falling by 43% over the past 20 years, with only about twenty million left.
The African Lion is listed as a vulnerable animal by this organization.
Ganswint said, "If we don't do something for this animal, they're going to be extinct."
He said that this new technology does not need to be given to the lions for breeding, but simply injects sperm into the fertilized lion's body, just as North America and Europe do with captive elephants.
