Nagoya, Nov 5 (Reuters) - Bank of Japan Governor Haruhiko Kuroda said on Monday that the central bank is aware that long-term implementation of ultra-loose monetary policy could squeeze the margins of financial institutions and potentially destabilize the country's banking system.
But he said the BOJ needed to maintain its massive stimulus package in light of sluggish inflation and the uncertainty of its overseas economies, while closely monitoring the pros and cons of its policies.
“The Bank of Japan fully acknowledges that the strength of financial institutions will be increasingly affected under the continued monetary easing, ” Kuroda said in a speech to Nagoya ’ s corporate leaders.
If financial institutions are more actively engaged in risks to compensate for the impact of shrinking margins caused by low interest rates over the years, there is a risk of turmoil in the banking system in the event of a severe negative impact.
“Although these risks are not great at the moment, the central bank will closely monitor the development of the situation and encourage financial institutions to take necessary measures, ” he said.
Minutes of the Bank of Japan's meeting, released earlier on Monday, showed that at the September meeting, the Bank of Japan's policy committee discussed the rising cost of long-term easing policy.
According to a member, the minutes said that if the economy continued to expand, “the BOJ has more room for flexibility in terms of policy in the future. ”
The minutes showed that another member said that in view of its limitations during the duration of the policy, the committee should discuss how long the BOJ could maintain stimulus.
Kuroda said that the Bank of Japan will assess the financial risks posed by easing policies, and at the same time need to consider the uncertainty surrounding Japan's economic prospects, which may affect global demand due to Sino-US trade frictions and rising protectionism.
“The impact of such problems on the Japanese economy is temporarily limited, ” Kuroda said.
“But how the problem continues, and the impact on the Japanese economy could be greater, ” he added.
“There is a need for sustained and robust monetary easing while considering positive and negative impacts in a balanced way, ” Kuroda said.
Despite the growing drawbacks of aggressive stimulus packages, such as long-term low interest rates eroding financial institutions' profits, sluggish inflation has forced the Bank of Japan to maintain the plan.
The Bank of Japan maintained monetary policy last month; in the face of the risks posed by a global trade war dispute, Kuroda ruled out the possibility of a recent rate hike.
