Han gin chicken soup exports to China surged 20x analysis in the past four years: related to the increase of empty nest youth
Yonhap News Agency reported on the 5th that South Korea's ginseng chicken soup exports to China last year amounted to more than $100,000, which surged about 20 times from 2013 four years ago.
According to the analysis, this increase is related to the increase of empty nest youth in China, which has led to the popular sales of convenient food, and the attention of young people to nutritious meals.
The data was published on the 5th by the Korea Agricultural and Aquatic Food Circulation Corporation (aT) on the 5th.
Last year, South Korea's ginseng chicken soup exports to China amounted to $10.0339 million, weighing 2.1859 million kilograms, which surged 2094 percent and 3668.8 percent respectively in 2013.
According to the analysis, the increase in the sales of chicken soup in South Korea is related to the increase of empty nest youth driving the hot sales of convenient food, as well as the attention of young people to nutritious meals.
As of this year, one-person households in China have broken through the two billion mark, and it is expected to increase to 30% of the total population in 2020, and local food companies have also targeted the "single rice family" to launch a variety of convenient food.
In addition, the analysis also said that avian influenza is the biggest factor hindering the ginseng chicken soup to take root in the mainland Chinese market.
aT said that from November 2016 to April last year, there was a bird flu epidemic in South Korea, and the relevant departments completely banned the export of ginseng chicken soup to China, resulting in a sharp reduction in export volume.
Exports of ginseng chicken soup to China amounted to $84 million in 2016, and exports plunged to $10 million last year due to bird flu.
