TOKYO, Oct 1 (Reuters) - Confidence in Japan's large manufacturingers in the quarter of September touched their lowest level in more than a year, according to the Bank of Japan's short-view survey quarterly report on Monday, due to rising raw material costs and a series of natural disasters affecting production, which has put companies at the pressure.
The survey shows little that escalating global trade frictions have hit the confidence of large manufacturers.
But the risk of a full-blown trade war has hit a business outlook and could threaten corporate capital spending.
Active capital spending is a bright spot in the Japanese economy.
The survey calls into question the Bank of Japan's view that a solid economic expansion will help drive inflation to its 2 percent target, despite signs that companies are gradually shifting costs to customers.
“With the global trade war raising concerns, the confidence of manufacturers has stagnated due to slowing exports and weak factory production, ” said Nan Wuzhi, chief researcher at the Institute of Agriculture and Forestry.
"Confidence is still high. And because corporate profits are improving and prices rise, I don't think confidence will continue to decline."
The short-term survey showed that the large manufacturing boom judgment index fell from positive 21 three months ago to positive 19, which was deteriorating for the third consecutive quarter.
The median estimate of the market is positive 22.
The September large non-manufacturing sentiment judgment index fell to positive22 from the June survey on positive22, the first deterioration in eight quarters.
The Reuters investigation is positive 22.
The survey shows that the index of large manufacturing and non-manufacturing boom judgments in December is expected to remain stable.
Investors did not care about the decline in the short-term corporate sentiment, and the Nikkei index .N2225 rose to a 27-year high on Monday, as the continued depreciation of the yen helped improve the export earnings prospects of Japanese companies.
Capital expenditures are robust.
Despite the decline in business confidence, the latest short-term highlights the robustness of corporate capital spending plans, driven by newer capacity and increased investment in robotics and automation to cope with labor shortages caused by an aging population.
The central bank's short-sighted survey showed that large enterprises plan to raise capital spending by 11.4 percent in the current fiscal year, which ended in March 2019.
The previous short-view survey was 13.6 percent.
Nan said that all corporate capital expenditure plans to grow by 8.5% this fiscal year, close to the pace of the Japanese bubble economy era.
“Given that small businesses are raising their profit estimates from now on, there is still room for capital spending to grow further, but much depends on the impact of the trade war on business confidence, ” he said.
The short-sightedness survey showed an increased ability of companies to pass on costs and the positive seven-year output price index for large enterprises, a decade-long high, a sign of encouraging and reflecting progress in Japan's efforts to combat deflation.
The index, which measures the employment situation of large enterprises, touched negative 23, the most tight level since 1992, highlighting the tightening of the job market.
Benefiting from strong corporate spending, the Japanese economy rebounded in the second quarter from a contraction in the first quarter of this year.
But the escalating trade frictions in the summer and the disruption of supply chains to natural disasters have clouded Japan's export-dependent economic outlook.
