The 69th International Astronautical Congress Opens in Germany
Xinhua News Agency, Germany's Bremen October 1st (Reporter Ren Ke Zhang Yirong) The 69th International Astronautical Congress kicked off on October 11th at the Bremen Convention and Exhibition Center in Germany, attended by more than 6,300 astronauts, space agencies and business representatives, experts, scholars and young students from all over the world.
Jean-Ye-Lehgar, president of the International Astronautical Federation, said in his speech at the opening ceremony that the global space industry is no longer only a few countries and institutions participating, and the number of participants this year has increased significantly compared to the previous one, indicating that more and more institutions and people are joining.
He called on countries to strengthen cooperation and innovation and jointly promote the development of the space industry.
Zhang Kejian, China's vice minister of industry and information technology and director of the State Department of Space, introduced China's space program when he attended the exchange event, and said that China will expand international cooperation in the space field and contribute to the human space industry.
Representatives of relevant institutions such as China Aerospace Science and Technology Group Corporation, and some private enterprises attended the meeting, showing the latest achievements of China's spaceflight, including various launch vehicles, satellites and aerospace science and technology application products.
The International Astronautical Congress has been held annually since 1950 and is the world's largest event in the world aviation community.
The conference is held for five days and co-sponsored by the International Astronautical Federation, the International Academy of Astronautics, the Center for Applied Science and Technology and Microgravity of the University of Bremen, and the International Space Law Society.
