Foreign media: The United States and Canada have reached a framework agreement on the North American Free Trade Agreement.
The agreement includes Canada's opening of its dairy market to the United States, and the U.S. will not impose tariffs on Canadian-made cars for the time being.
According to foreign media reports, a Canadian source revealed on the evening of September 30th that the United States and Canada have reached a framework agreement on the North American Free Trade Agreement.
According to the statement, the agreement includes Canada's opening of its dairy market to the United States, and the United States will not impose tariffs on Canadian-made cars for the time being.
On the 27th of last month, the United States and Mexico announced a preliminary agreement in principle on updating the North American Free Trade Agreement, but the United States and Canada failed to reach an agreement before the August 31 deadline set by the United States to extend the negotiation period until September 30th.
Earlier, a spokesman for Foreign Minister Chrystia Freeland said Canada would only sign favorable agreements, "with a focus on substance, not timetable. We will continue to negotiate and hope to reach an agreement that is in line with Canada's national interests."
More than nine out of ten Brazilian women voters said the presidential candidates did not take into account the needs of women.
According to a recent data released by the National Geographic Institute of Brazil (IBGE), more than 90% of Brazilian women do not think that presidential candidates consider the needs of women.
At present, the number of women in Brazil has reached 1.07 billion, and if the whole of Brazil's women is gathered to form a country, the country's population will rank 13th in the world, more than two times the number of people in Spain.
In Brazil, the number of female voters makes up 52 percent of the total electorate and 48% for men, and while women are very high among voters, the proportion of women in Brazil's Congress is only 10%.
In 193 countries around the world, Brazil's women's participation in politics is only 154th, higher than in Arab countries.
After more than two decades of struggle over the rights struggle, Brazilian women still have not succeeded in gaining the rights they deserve.
Brazilian sociologist Natalia Mori points out that the phenomenon is due to the result of the combination of ancient patriarchal societies, racism and the role of capitalist values.
"Politics should be the people who claim the rights of citizens, their identities, the acquisition of public goods and the same society, and the same society. But Brazil's politics belongs to a monopoly of a certain group, and the majority of the population is not represented."
A previous study by the Locomotiva Institute of Brazil also pointed out that 94% of Brazilian women do not feel that the elected politicians can represent their rights, 90% of Brazilian women do not agree with the decisions made by politicians, and 93% do not agree with the current government's governance policies.
"We need to reverse the problem of underrepresentation of women in parliament, and Brazil's political system is still affected by inequality. So far, there is still a serious gender, class and racial discrimination in Brazil's political sphere," Natalia Mori said.
Despite women's underrepresented rights, most Brazilian women still believe in the power of democracy.
The survey showed that 76% of women believe they can make a difference in the democratic elections, and 72 per cent of women are interested in politics.
In addition, 55 percent of women believe that democracy is the best way to expose women to less prejudice.
