HONG KONG (Reuters) - Hong Kong property prices have fallen back after peaking for two consecutive months, Hong Kong's Monetary Authority President Chen Delin said on Monday that it takes time to see if the property market has entered a downward cycle, and if confirmed, it can be considered that the tightening of counter-cyclical measures can be considered at an appropriate time.
Chen Delin also pointed out that if the real estate price is adjusted, the first time it will be affected people who will be affected at the peak of the property market, but it is expected that the price of the property will fall at the time of the Asian financial storm in 1997, and the opportunity for the public to sell the property is much lower.
Chen Delin led a number of senior executives of the HKMA to the Legislative Council briefing, saying that if it is confirmed that the property market has entered a downward cycle, measures can be relaxed in due course.
"But at present, only a few weeks of data, the relaxation is still too early, there is still more time to see whether the property market has entered a downward cycle."
Since 2009, the HKMA has introduced eight rounds of counter-cyclical measures to significantly tighten mortgages for various types of properties, including reducing the number of mortgages and the need for mortgage applicants to pass rigorous stress tests to enhance bank risk management and earthquake resistance.
As Hong Kong officially entered a rate hike cycle, the Hong Kong-wide private residential real estate price index peaked for two consecutive months in August-September, and the monthly decline in September expanded to 1.44%.
But the cumulative increase in the first three quarters of this year is still 10.2%.
According to the HKMA, the financial situation of families with earthquake resistance to financial risks is still healthy. In the second quarter of this year, the ratio of self-occupation residents with no mortgages in Hong Kong reached 66%, which is higher than the average of 60% in 2009-11; the average number of new mortgages and the income ratio of new mortgages and the income ratio of new mortgages are 47% and 34%, respectively, and have improved significantly compared to 64% and 41% respectively in 2009-11%.
But Chen Delin said that the high earthquake resistance does not mean that the already real estate citizens will not be damaged by the economic downturn, because the property valuation will fall, and the people who buy buildings at the peak will bear the brunt.
While the HKMA has tightened up bank lending to mortgage lenders, property owners can also get high-quality mortgages through mortgage insurance or by developers.
Chen Delin said that at present, together with mortgage loans provided to developers, the number of mortgages in borrowers can reach 85-90%, and if the property price falls by one percent, there will be negative assets (i.e., the market value of properties falling below the total amount of unrendered mortgages).
However, Nguyen Guoheng, vice president of the HKMA, pointed out that the total amount of mortgages estimated by the developers to provide a high number of mortgages, only accounts for 2-2.5 percent of the total bank mortgages, and the proportion is still low.
At the peak of Hong Kong's negative assets in 2003, the number of negative assets exceeded 100,000, accounting for 22 percent of the number of people in the supply.
As of the third quarter of this year, Hong Kong recorded zero negative assets for seven consecutive quarters.
