Systematic lupus erythematosus is a chronic problem of tired and multi-organizing organs throughout the body, and has been considered "unsustainable disease" in the past.
Because its pathogenesis is unknown, diagnosis and treatment are difficult to find, and there is no cure for effective treatment.
Recently, Liu Wanli, a researcher at the School of Life Sciences of Tsinghua University, and the director of the Center for Rheu-Wemmun Immunology at Peking University People's Hospital, Knutoro, found that there are molecular variants that increase systemic lizum erythematosus sluphosis, and this variant is involved in regulating immune B cells.
In short, the two teams confirmed that an abnormal immune molecule in the human body is an important cause of the onset of systemic lupus erythematosus.
According to Sun Xiaolin, one of the authors of the article and the Peking University People's Hospital, the Chestnut National team collected nearly 2000 large samples of systemic lupus erythematosus patients and conducted research and found that patients with immunoglobulin variants produced disease-causing cells and a wide range of species, a large number of autoantibodies, nephritis, arthritis, generalitis, vasculitis and other inflammation, the incidence and severity of inflammation increased significantly.
Through a variety of research methods such as immune cell stracity, animal testing, and sequencing, Liu Wanli's team found the immune signaling pathway activated by this immune molecular variant and promoted the pathogenic mechanism of B cells secreting a variety of autoantibodies.
The reporter learned that the two teams are strong and united, giving full play to their respective advantages, and realizing the close integration of basic research and clinical applications.
Liu Wanli's team is committed to B lymphocyte immunocommentation and immuno-reactive research, while the Chestnut Country team has long been engaged in clinical research on systemic lupus erythematosus.
"This study is one of the results of many years of cooperation between the two teams, and for the first time in the academic community has recognized that immunoglobulin gene abnormalities will induce systemic lizum erytheusus, laying a solid foundation for further academic research and clinical targeted therapies."
