Since the mid-2000s, as China's demand for oilseeds has grown, U.S. North Dakota farmer Paul Thomas has planted more and more soybeans in his land.
The shift peaked at the peak this year, and he planted 1,600 acres of soybeans in 5,000 acres, reaching a size that had never been seen before.
But Thomas and many farmers like him plan to convert to staple crops in the former U.S. agricultural region in 2019: corn and wheat.
U.S. farmers have more soybean cultivation this year than corn, for the first time in 35 years.
The reason for the transfer of other food crops is that American farmers are facing difficulties in selling soybeans against the backdrop of U.S. President Donald Trump's trade war against China.
China typically buy about 60 percent of U.S. soybeans, but because of the trade war, almost zero purchases of U.S. soybeans in recent months, has caused soybean prices to fall to a decade-old low.
Thomas intends to grow more wheat next year, hoping to make more money by reducing his reliance on crops that depend on China's needs.
Thomas said soybean prices "bring us a blow to our pain."
He said that without China's purchase needs, the spot price of soybeans near its farm is $7.10 per bushel, and the price necessary to cover the cost is $8.50.
U.S. farmers have set a record high in soybean cultivation this year, and the harvest is also expected to hit a record high.
Just in such an easy-to-hit moment, they've been hit by a trade war.
In response to Trump's tariffs on imported Chinese goods, China imposed import tariffs on U.S. soybeans in July.
The USDA will release its first estimate of acreage next year, which is expected to include considerations of the impact on the tariffs.
It is expected that the estimate will confirm the expectation that the soybean planting area will be reduced by private institutions.
According to a report seen by Reuters, Informatica Economics expects corn acres to increase by 4% to 9,270 million acres (37,5.5 million hectares) in 2019, and soybean acres will be reduced by 7% to 8.3 million acres.
Informa also expects a 4% increase in U.S. wheat acreage.
The area of soybeans planted before retaliatory tariffs rose to 8,960 million acres this year, up about 11,5 million acres higher than a decade ago.
The corn-growing area has increased by less than 5 million acres since 2008 to 8,9.1 million acres, and wheat cultivation this year is 4,780 million acres, close to the lowest level in 100 years.
Iron Carlson, president of the Illinois Corn Plow Association, has a total of 3,600 acres of its own, and nearly half of him will be used to grow soybeans this year, but plans to cut back in the future.
He said it could increase corn cultivation by up to 20 percent on his farm in northern Illinois; the state is the largest soybean-growing state in the U.S.
Soybeans produce less than corn per acre, but they also require less fertilizer, which makes soybeans generally lower the cost of planting.
If farmers move to the final value of corn, it may raise costs, but it will benefit some businesses, including Andersons Inc., a fertiliser seller.
Andersons chief executive Pat Bowe told Reuters he expected the conversion of corn to be beneficial for fertilizer use.
Bayer is also expected to benefit from the conversion of farmers to corn.
