BEIJING, Sept 30 (Reuters) - China's central bank on Sunday released data showing that the central bank's foreign currency-to-norm side of the local currency forward contract and futures contract short margin position as of the end of August this year was zero for 12 consecutive months, and there were still long positions in the month.
The central bank's previous data showed that as of the end of August last year, the central bank held a total of $60.44 billion in foreign currency to the far-term forward contract and futures contract short position, unchanged for the fourth consecutive month; the size of the short position in the SDR (Special Drawing Rights) was 42.76 billion SDRs.
Since then, the central bank's foreign exchange forward short position has been zero.
The central bank first released the data at the end of March 2016; the data showed that the central bank's foreign currency for the local currency forward contract and futures contract long position at the end of February 2016 was 24.38 billion dollars, and the short position was $289 billion.
September data released at the end of October of the same year showed a net short increase of $164.01 million to $453.01 billion.
The central bank has previously said that the forward and futures short positions in foreign currencies in the local currency mainly reflect the foreign exchange forward operation carried out by the central bank to meet the demand for the hedging of the foreign currency liabilities of enterprises and commercial banks, and will continue to provide forward-term safe-haven products according to the principle of real needs, and the long-term operation of the central bank has less impact on the scale of future foreign exchange reserves.
