The first joint visit of the Han River into the sea in 65 years
South Korea's Defense Ministry confirmed on the 5th that the two Koreas launched a joint inspection of the waters of the Han River and the Linjin River into Haikou on the same day.
The initiative is an upfront preparation to guarantee the freedom of civil vessels of both sides.
The South Korean Defense Ministry's briefing to the media on the same day showed that this was the first time that the two sides have conducted a joint expedition to the Han River into Haikou since the signing of the Armistice Agreement of the Korean War in 1953.
The two Koreas signed a military agreement in September this year, and agreed to jointly visit the waters such as the Han River into Haikou from November to ensure the future protection of the waters and the development of tourism.
In October, the two Koreas planned a joint expedition to the waters at a general-level meeting.
On November 5th, the joint inspection of inter-Korean waters was officially launched.
The joint mission is composed of 20 people, including the Korean military and experts.
According to the South Korean Defense Ministry, during the visit, neither of the personnel of the two sides was carrying weapons, and the use of words and deeds that stimulated each other was prohibited.
"Because there is no military demarcation line near the sea, the area was once an unexpected high area, but through joint expeditions, it will become a new peaceful lot in the future."
The waters of the joint inter-Korean expedition, with a total length of about 70 kilometers and a total area of about 280 square kilometers.
According to the South Korean Defense Ministry, the ROK side will send six inspection ships to carry out exploration of the depth of the seawater, etc., to provide basic information for the safe navigation of the waters; after the investigation is completed, it will provide a navigation map for the movement of civilian ships.
The two Koreas held summit talks in Pyongyang in October 2007 to reach an agreement on jointly using the Han River and the Linjin River to enter the sea mouth, but follow-up talks were stranded due to tensions on the peninsula.
According to the military agreement signed by the two Koreas in September, ships of the two sides need to be informed in advance of the other side before sailing in common waters in the future.
